I think we should let the price float with the market instead of trying to=20
forecast it. Otherwise, if our forecast is not consistence with the market,=20
we may have an imbalance in the bid-ask orders and we may end up taking some=
=20
positions. You know, as Russ and Martin pointed out, we cannot fight with th=
e=20
studio and exhibitors because they have inside information and can game the=20
price easily.

One way to ensure the balance of the bid-ask orders is to embed an exchange=20
system inside our bid-ask prices front end. Each week, we have a trading=20
period. During the period, instead of posting bid-ask prices, we post=20
"tentative" bid-ask prices, then we ask our customers to submit their=20
acceptable buying or selling price. These "tentative" bid-ask prices get=20
updated and are shown to the public. Of course, customers can revise/withdra=
w=20
their bids anytime during the trading period. At the end of the period, we=20
calculate and post the final bid and ask prices. The seller who submits lowe=
r=20
selling price than our final bid price gets paid at the bid price. The buyer=
=20
who submits higher buying price than our final ask price pays at the ask=20
price. Next week, we repeat the same process.

This way, we can manage our positions easily and we can also behave like a=20
broker where we don't take any position at all. We make profit from those=20
bid-ask spread. We don't have to worry about forecasting accuracy and=20
insiders' trading because we don't have to take any position. Let the market=
=20
be the one who decides the price.=20

If we maintain our net position as zero, at the end, when all the actual=20
gross box office numbers are reported in those publications, our customers=20
with open long/short positions are perfectly matched. Using the=20
mark-to-market charge can reduce credit risk.

